  <data name="richTextBox1.Text" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Quickdoc do create a mod: (only useful for devs; hope it lasts for now)

- create a new .net dll project
- Add reference ModController.dll
- Create a public class, directly in a namespace, that implements Faark.Gnomoria.Modding.Mod or IMod
- at the end the dll should be placed in gnomorias folder subfolder "mods" (eg c:\programme\gnomoria\mods\mymod.dll)
- modui.exe automatically scans for those classes in those dlls and querys
- avoid the constructor of your mod-stuff. Can't be sure atm that all assemblys are loaded there. use the virtual stuff in imod instead
- GetConfig is the important part that defines how you "hook" into the game
- u should return sth like new ModConfig( this, insert_hooks_here )
- Hooks are the difficult part. Use reflection to get the exact MethodInfo you want to hook into. Then do the same for an own static function.
- How your method for the hook must look:
       static returntype blabla( [parent_result, ][this, ][arguments] );

where:
 - arguments are obviousely exactly the args the hooked function takes
 - (only valid for non-static stuff) this is the objects type of hooked method, if it isn't static 
 - (only valid when using InjectAfter &amp; if hooked function isn't void) parent_result is the result, that was returned form the hooked function, otherwise void
 - (only valid when using InjectAfter or Replace &amp; if hooked function isn't void) return value, using this you can manipulate the hooked functions result. should be return parent_result in most cases

ps: "Valid" means mandatory :)

yet known limitation:
 - dont use anything but InjectAfter on constructors

other notes:
 - watch for performance. try to avoid critical stuff and and don't overuse e.g. reflection, if somehow possible
 - you use anything on your own risk and "as is". feel free to leave me a message, but i can't promise anything!</value>
